## Problem Statement

Noob Aggregate Weekly Forecast pipeline is ready but not yet configured for markdown clients. The pipeline needs to be tested end to end to make sure that it can work with tiny adjustments to configuration for different clients. The goal is to easily onboard existing and new clients and make the pipeline a part of 3 day dag.

- Slow sellers in hierarchy pairs are cleaned by adding the following section to user_extra_config in forecast_coefficients_data_prep section of the config file. For further information about how you can generate low_sales pairs, you can check the guide.

```
user_extra_info_config:
    add:
      - name: low_sales
        metadata_name: cl_attributes_low_sales
        join_keys:
          - product_agg_level
          - store_agg_level
        join_columns:
          - low_sales_pair
        how: left_anti
        rename: false
```

- Remove other outliers in the data. (dates with low stock)
- Add the most granular level of aggregation as one of the aggregation_levels. If a pair has history of more than 1 year, the best seasonality curve will usually be of itself. Adding a granular level lengthens the training process. So to make sure we’re not working on pairs which will not reveal good curves, we’re altering sales_df property of ForecastCoefficientsTrain module as follows:

        sales_df = sales_df.join(set,"target_column","inner")

        return sales_df

Lockdown doesn’t mean all the dates where sales are 0, it can also mean reduced sales etc. If ignore tables are all set and correct for your project pass use_only_usable_periods parameters as True. - Add promo discount bins as holidays.
- Do not just use the holiday_table dates, analyze the client’s data and pick the dates for sales uplifts. Countries or clients still may have different dynamics for different holidays. E.g. in SA Black Friday effects are usually 1 week later than other countries. Or in general BackToSchool might cover 3 weeks each year in the holiday_table, but really the effects are only in 1 week. Also Ramazan (Eid Al Fitr) & Kurban (Eid Al Adha) peak dates are changeable. For example to capture the peak sales for Ramazan below code seems to work. The assumption is when Ramazan is close, sales are increased for 3 weeks, one of the 3 weeks sees a steep increase. The code below selects the highest sale week and labels it as ‘peak_Ramazan’, the other 2 weeks are labeled as ‘effect_Ramazan’.

- Sudden sales increase can be because of promo or holidays. Make sure that when you sales increases your promo or holiday data can cover it. If you can’t explain the data with promo or holiday and it’s not a seasonal increase, remove the data from your train dataset.

- Slow sellers bottom threshold level was set as 0.95 previously. This number is updated to 0.85. (ForecastCoefficientsDataPrep)
- Dates with sudden sales increases & decreases, that can not be explained by an occasion are removed from the data. (ForecastCoefficientsDataPrep)
- cl_weekly_broken_assortment information is added to the input_data. product_agg_level, store_agg_level pairs with broken assortment value less than 0.75 are removed from the data. (ForecastCoefficientsDataPrep)

    def sales_df(self) -> DataFrame:
        """
        Read sales data from path given in config

        :return: sales_df
        :rtype: DataFrame
        """
        df = self.data.try_read(name=self.input_table_name)
        df = df.filter("date >= '2019-02-03'")
        df = join_extra_info(df, self.extra_info, self.log)
        df = df.filter("broken_assortment >= 0.75")
        df = df.drop("broken_assortment")
        return df

Chain Weekly Forecast is used to generate forecast based on aggregated product-store levels on a weekly basis. Aggregation levels for product-store are adjustable and can be assigned to any hierarchy. Chain level modules use product_agg_level & store_agg_level columns from `cl_store_agg_level_historic` and `cl_product_agg_level_historic`. The default for product_agg_level & store_agg_level are product_code & country respectively.

Generated forecast is at default 84 days/12 weeks, and is given in commons config with `chain_long_term_forecast_horizon` parameter. The horizon can be increased/decreased according to client's needs.

At default, dag produces two forecasts, LinearRegression & LGBM

### Getting Started

Before getting started with chain weekly forecast, remember that forecasts in this pipeline are ml models and will need iteration, feature engineering & analyzing. The default settings are just suggestions and may not always be aligned with your client’s/product’s needs.

You’ll be able to generate & check most of the tables you’ll need with the guides provided, you’ll have tools to analyze & visualize your output. Also you can check ml guidelines to help you with forecast iteration & go-live.  add ml guidelines

. Also you can check ml guidelines to help you with forecast iteration & go-live.  add ml guidelines

Make sure your client has all tables you’ll need for forecasting. Default tables used in the dag are listed below, but these can be removed, or new tables can be added. This document will try to explain at best which tables are used for what, what additional tables may be needed, which may be removed according to client or product. For example price_steps table is needed only for markdown clients. Make sure that the tables you’ll use have correct data, are not duplicated, etc.  (add data control guideline. E.g is the usable column in daily-data filled correctly, check that all usables are 0 for covid period, lockdown etc. If not communicate with other people in the project and consider recreating daily-data.

#### Asp - Discount

[Asp](https://gitlab.com/invent-analytics/sparky/rocks-noob/-/blob/main/rocks/noob/promotion/asp_calculation.py) module calculates asp, group_asp & base_price from daily data. [Discount](https://gitlab.com/invent-analytics/sparky/rocks-noob/-/blob/main/rocks/noob/promotion/discount_calculation.py) module takes asp module output and combines it with client’s existing price & first_price data and calculates discount_rate & discount_bin. If the client has an unreliable or incomplete price or first_price, group_asp for price & base_price for first_price is used to fill the gaps. In chain weekly context [cl_weekly_asp_calculation](https://gitlab.com/invent-analytics/sparky/rocks-noob/-/blob/main/rocks/noob/config.yml#L3861-3900) & [cl_weekly_discount_calculation](https://gitlab.com/invent-analytics/sparky/rocks-noob/-/blob/main/rocks/noob/config.yml#L4012-4075) config sections are used

t-analytics/sparky/rocks-noob/-/blob/main/rocks/noob/config.yml#L4012-4075) config sections are used. Check out promo modules [guide](https://gitlab.com/invent-analytics/quality-team/-/blob/main/notebooks/noob-promo-guide.ipynb) to run the module & analyze the outputs. To calculate discount bins, discount calculation module requires discount bin borders to be given in the config. These borders are best adjusted according to client’s data. This [guide](https://gitlab.com/invent-analytics/quality-team/-/blob/main/notebooks/promo/weekly_discount_bin_calculation.ipynb) can be used to decide on borders.

If the client’s price data is unreliable or missing promo module will be the main source of price & discount information. So the configuration & analysis of the output will be important. #### LowSales

[LowSales](https://gitlab.com/invent-analytics/sparky/rocks-noob/-/blob/main/rocks/noob/attributes/low_sales.py) module aims to flag low-selling pairs in a hierarchical grouping. The module aggregates & sums sales from daily data according to `cluster_by` parameter, sorts sum of sales in decreasing order in `cluster_inside` and calculates cumulative sum of sales. So each pair is sorted from best selling to worst selling in its hierarchy. Then cumulativs sum of sales is divided by the total sum of sales in the hierarchy and a percentage is obtained. When the percentage exceeds `bottom_threshold`, the pairs are flagged as low_sales. These pairs are low-sellers and have very little contribution to hierarchy’s sales. The default parameters of the module can be seen from the [config](https://gitlab.com/invent-analytics/sparky/rocks-noob/-/blob/main/rocks/noob/config.yml#L2891-2930) (`cl_low_sales`)

#### Chain Weekly Enrich

[ChainWeeklyEnrich](https://gitlab.com/invent-analytics/sparky/rocks-noob/-/blob/main/rocks/noob/enrich/chain_weekly.py) module prepares the base data to be used in forecasting. Daily data is *aggregated* from daily to weekly basis & from product-store id level to product-store agg level.

is *aggregated* from daily to weekly basis & from product-store id level to product-store agg level.

In the module, at first, tables in [daily_extra_config](https://gitlab.com/invent-analytics/sparky/rocks-noob/-/blob/main/rocks/noob/config.yml#L2437-2470) is joined to daily data. Then the data is aggregated to product-store agg level with the [first round](https://gitlab.com/invent-analytics/sparky/rocks-noob/-/blob/main/rocks/noob/config.yml#L2328-2374) of aggregations performed. At this point the first interim table is saved (`1-0`). Then [extra_info_config](https://gitlab.com/invent-analytics/sparky/rocks-noob/-/blob/main/rocks/noob/config.yml#L2415-2436) tables are joined, then the data is aggregated to weekly with the [second round](https://gitlab.com/invent-analytics/sparky/rocks-noob/-/blob/main/rocks/noob/config.yml#L2375-2414) of aggregations performed. The second interim table is saved here (`1-1`).

ob/config.yml#L2375-2414) of aggregations performed. The second interim table is saved here (`1-1`).

Then usable_ratio is calculated and the third interim tables is saved (`2`).

Enrich data is created from actual data up until run_date. After run_date the data is extended to future by `forecast_horizon/7` number of weeks. This future_data includes only the pairs given in `fc_scope`.

In the final step, week, month etc information is collected from the calendar and enrich is saved.

[Link to config](https://gitlab.com/invent-analytics/sparky/rocks-noob/-/blob/main/rocks/noob/config.yml#L2300-2470). (`chain_weekly_enrich`)

#### BrokenAssortment

rokenAssortment

[Broken assortment](https://gitlab.com/invent-analytics/sparky/rocks-noob/-/blob/main/rocks/noob/feature_engineering/broken_assortment.py) is a KPI to see if all sizes of an option can be found in all the stores it has sold. For a pair it is calculated as MIN(1, Inventory/(SizeCount*MAX(StoreCount))). At default week start inventory is used. Basically if an option has 5 sizes (XS, S, M, L, XL) and at its peak it has sold in 300 stores in the store agg level (eg. country) it needs at least 1500 inventory to keep one of each in all the stores. Anything below that, it is considered broken. This metric is used heavily in markdown forecast but can be useful for other products as well. [Link to config](https://gitlab.com/invent-analytics/sparky/rocks-noob/-/blob/main/rocks/noob/config.yml#L4145-4164). [Link to module guide](https://gitlab.com/invent-analytics/quality-team/-/blob/main/notebooks/chain-weekly/cl-weekly-broken-assortment.ipynb). (`cl_weekly_broken_assortment`)

#### LagFeatures

This [module](https://gitlab.com/invent-analytics/sparky/rocks-noob/-/blob/main/rocks/noob/enrich/lag_features.py) generates lag features from chain weekly enrich dataframe, according to [config](https://gitlab.com/invent-analytics/sparky/rocks-noob/-/blob/main/rocks/noob/config.yml#L1823-1879). There are 2 kinds of lags generated: lags & conditional_ma_lags. Regular lags are x period lags of `features`, at `groupby_features` level. Lags period, features to be lagged, groupby_features etc. are all configurable. Conditional MA Lags create MA Lags, with ranges in `ma_ranges`, at `groupby_features` level. Also filters can be added to conditional_ma_lags, so ma windows will be filtered and then ma will be calculated. For example `in_season = False & low_sales = False` can be filtered out from MA Lags. Any table can be added using `extra_info_config` to be used in filters. With this capability demand-like features can be calculated

xtra_info_config` to be used in filters. With this capability demand-like features can be calculated. #### MarkdownDefaultScenario

The aim of [MarkdownDefaultScenario](https://gitlab.com/invent-analytics/sparky/rocks-noob/-/blob/main/rocks/noob/scenario_creation/markdown_default_scenario.py) module is to create a scenario dataframe for markdown forecast. The default markdown scenario consists of discount rates different price steps & discount steps in addition to latest price & first_price combined for a pair, with a broken_assortment value of 1. Also there are 2 flags: `current_price_flag` shows the latest current price of the pair at the given run_date, `is_discount_step` shows if the price in the scenario comes from a price_step or a discount_step. The module has no date dimension, it only creates the scenario at the given run_date. Check out the module [guide](https://gitlab.com/invent-analytics/quality-team/-/blob/main/notebooks/chain-weekly/markdown-default-scenario.ipynb) to see to analyse the output of the module.
